  "text": "As described in Section II, the intensity computation (10) involves a nonlinear process that complicates the analysis of statistical properties in the intensity signal. Our theoretical work builds on earlier results by Wagner et al. [CITATION_1] that allows for first and second moments (i.e., mean and autocovariance) of the intensity signal to be calculated. We have extended Wagner's analysis, which focused on two-point statistics, to a linear systems approach where individual points are placed in the context of a system function and acquisition noise.",
